node.text:
If there were a competition for the most beautiful cheese, Cornish Yarg would claim the title. Each cheese is wrapped in wild stinging nettles, which are brushed on by hand one by one. With aging, the nettles form a natural rind around the cheese, giving it a fresh, creamy taste with hints of herbs, mushrooms, seaweed, and even lemon. So how did this recipe even come about? It was actually found randomly in a book about 400 years ago. We visited Lynher Dairies in the heart of Cornwall to find out more.

#cornishyarg #cheese #dairy #cornwall

node.title: How Cornish Yarg cheese is made | Regional Eats

node.text:
Bury, Lancashire, England is know for being the capital of black pudding. The sausage made of cereals and blood is a delicacy here, eaten as a takeaway food with sauce or in a bread roll. Richard Morris from the Bury Black Pudding Company takes us through the making process step by step. His grandfather was a butcher, and it is his black pudding recipe that the company uses today.

Featuring @clacly22

Popcorn is Illinois' official snack food, and @garrettpopcorn has been serving some of the best handcrafted popcorn in the state since 1949. The secret family recipe that's been handed down over three generations is still made in old-fashioned copper kettles with kernels that are grown just for the company. Garrett's handcrafts its popcorn in small batches throughout the day and can make anywhere from 30 to 150 batches daily. The famous Garrett mix consists of a mix of its CheeseCorn and CaramelCrisp flavors, creating a perfect blend of savory and sweet. There's almost always a line at all Garrett Popcorn shops, so Insider's Medha Imam (@medhapedia) visited one to see how the iconic mix is made and why it's one of Oprah's "Favorite Things." 

Editor's Note: Insider visited Garrett Popcorn in March 2020, before Chicago restaurants closed to dine-in service. You can still order popcorn and more for pickup and delivery. For more information, visit: www.garrettpopcorn.com

Insider's Claudia Romeo (@clacly22) traveled to Seine-et-Marne, France to visit Ferme des 30 Arpents. The farm is one of seven farms making raw-milk Brie de Meaux cheese, and the only one that makes it fermier, which means that the cheese is made by hand solely with milk produced by the 250 cows at the farm. Every day, Ferme des 30 Arpents will make about 300 wheels of Brie de Meaux from its herd's milk.

Editor's note: This footage was filmed on February 14, 2020. At present, Ferme des 30 Arpents has implemented preventive measures to ensure everyone's safety and has adopted the health regulations in force for its production of farmhouse cheeses.

@Slusheeland, a dessert shop that specializes in fruit slushies, yogurt shakes, and shaved ice, has a new item on their menu called Mango Loco. It is a whole mango covered in tamarind chamoy paste and is supposed to be eaten with the skin on. The mango is cut into slices and topped with Japanese peanuts, tamarind candies, and chamoy sauce (a spicy, tangy Mexican candy sauce). Slusheeland has two California locations, in North Hollywood and Tarzana.

node.text:
@fugetsudo Confectionary first opened in 1903. It is now considered the oldest shop in LA’s Little Tokyo, and the oldest Japanese-American business in the country. The family-owned bakery is famous for one thing above all: mochi. 

Making this Japanese confection has been a long tradition for the Kito family, one that started over a century ago, when original owner Seiichi Kito first immigrated to the U.S from Japan. 

The art of making mochi is no easy feat, according to current owner Brian Kito, who says it took him 10 years to learn how to master the process.

Crystal Lee (@crystalclues) visited Fugetsu-Do’s original location in Los Angeles to see how they make their famous ‘rainbow dango’ (bite-sized pieces of rainbow mochi), and how this family business has survived 117 years.

node.text:
In a time when much of the world is facing lockdown because of the coronavirus pandemic, unable to see family and friends in person, many of us are turning to food for comfort. Different dishes are considered comfort food around the world, but they’re all typically high in sugar, fat, and salt. These flavors are key in not only making us feel happy but also in solidifying these dishes in our memories. Twenty people from different cultural backgrounds shared what their favorite comfort food is and what it means to them, and we looked at how their dish of choice is made. 

Featuring: @carolinemishelle, @rinnny_, @lisaparadise, @anewyorker, @realharrykersh 

#comfortfood #foodfromaroundtheworld #foodiesofinstagram #culture

node.title: 20 comfort foods from around the world

If there were a competition for the most beautiful cheese, Cornish Yarg would claim the title. Each cheese is wrapped in wild stinging nettles, which are brushed on by hand one by one. With aging, the nettles form a natural rind around the cheese, giving it a fresh, creamy taste with hints of herbs, mushrooms, seaweed, and even lemon. So how did this recipe even come about? It was actually found randomly in a book about 400 years ago. We visited Lynher Dairies in the heart of Cornwall to find out more.

node.text:
Jeff Simonian, president of Simonian Fruit Company, likes to enjoy pomegranate arils in champagne, on top of a salad, or in Jell-O. Look for pomegranates that are bright in color and heavy for their size to ensure juicy seeds. Score the peel to divide the fruit into quarters before pulling it apart with your hands. In a bowl of water, separate the arils (or seeds) from the white, inedible pith.

Click the link in our bio to read more.

(Credit: runner of art/Getty Images, Göksel Kaya / EyeEm/Getty Images)
#Pomegranate #Fruits #HowTo

node.accessibility_caption: Photo showing pomegranates with headline, "How to cut a pomegranate to get to the juicy seeds without making a mess"

Photo showing pomegranate peeling with text, "Cut off the crown: The fruit has a small, pointy protrusion on one end that looks like a crown. Use a sharp knife to slice off the crown along with a little of the white 
pith underneath."

Photo showing pomegranate peeling with text, "Slice into sections: Run a knife from the crown end all the way around the pomegranate, scoring the skin without slicing into the fruit and dividing into half. If you notice little ridges running down the length of your pomegranate, cut along those ridges. Repeat, dividing into quarters."
Photo showing pomegranate peeling with text, "Break apart: Grab each side with your hands and gently but firmly break in half along the scored lines. Break each half into quarters."

Photo showing pomegranate peeling with text, "Remove the arils: Simonian recommends placing the sections in a bowl of water and using your fingers to roll out the arils, separating them from the pith, which will float. You can also hold a section over a bowl, arils facing out, and whack the peel with a wooden spoon to dislodge the edible fruit. If you use this method, you will likely need to use your fingers to retrieve some more stubborn arils."
Photo showing pomegranate peeling with text, "Discard the peel and pith: The peel and white pith are inedible and should be tossed after retrieving the arils."

Celebrity chef Masaharu Morimoto first entered Americans' homes in 1999 when he landed a spot as one of the experts on "Iron Chef America" after competing on the Japanese version of the show in 1998. 

He went on to open his first restaurant at the age of 24, became the executive chef at Nobu after moving stateside, and continued to build his worldwide restaurant portfolio, the website adds. 

Through his cookbook, "Mastering the Art of Japanese Home Cooking," Morimoto shares his tips and tricks for creating traditional Japanese meals at home. 

In an email to Insider, the chef shared a recipe reminiscent of his early days as a student of sushi: temaki. 

Find the full recipe at the link in our bio.

Insider asked chefs to pick the best and worst seafood dishes to order at a restaurant. They said fluke is an underrated fish and deep-fried calamari may lack flavor. Chefs suggest avoiding seafood specials, as they could be hiding old fish.

Photo by Food Insider on September 01, 2021. May be an image of food and text that says 'INSIDER Pan-fried sea bass has a scrumptious texture. It normally has a light flavor on its own, so the seasoning or sauce that it's served with is crucial to the meal. Casey recommended asking for lemon juice, vinaigrette, or even garlic-infusec olive oil to liven up your dish.'.

Executive chef and former "Chopped" contestant Matt Ginr of Chebeague Island Inn told Insider that he loves ordering fluke when he spots it on a seafood menu. It's also known as summer flounder.'.

Photo by Food Insider on September 01, 2021. May be an image of text that says 'INSIDER Choose local fish for optimal freshness. When in doubt, ask your server what menu items use locally caught or harvested ingredients.'.

Photo by Food Insider on September 01, 2021. May be an image of food and text that says 'INSIDER Black cod is a rich and satisfying option. William Eick, executive chef and owner of Matsu in California, told Insidetaherecomendorderigblakck that he recommends ordering black cod.'.

Photo by Food Insider on September 01, 2021. May be an image of crustacean, food and text that says 'INSIDER Spot prawns are pricey but worth it. Spot prawns are sweet shrimp that resemble little lobsters and have a delicate texture.'.

node.text:
Insider’s Anneta Konstantinides recently made Ina Garten’s easy breakfast tacos, and the dish took her just 15 minutes.

Garten’s breakfast tacos include scrambled eggs, avocado slices, scallions, and Chipotle hot sauce.

Garten’s breakfast tacos appear in her most recent cookbook, “Modern Comfort Food.” She credits her social-media producer and recipe tester Kristina Feliz Ibarra with the recipe.

Click the link in our bio to read more about the recipe.

(Credit: Anneta Konstantinides/Insider)

node.accessibility_caption: Photo of two soft tacos with the headline, "I made Ina Garten's breakfast tacos, and the easy dish took me just 15 minutes."

Photo of scallions, tortillas, eggs, an avacado, cheese, and chipotle sauce with the text, "To make tacos for four people, you need eight extra-large eggs, eight white-corn tortillas (Garten recommends the 6-inch), six scallions, Monterey Jack cheese (grated), one avocado, and Chipotle or Tabasco sauce."

Photo of a tortilla on a cast iron pan and cheese on top with the text, "I kept a watchful eye on the tortillas as I toasted them, flipping when they just started to crisp. Then, I sprinkled some cheese on top of each. Garten recommends letting the cheese melt before transferring to a plate."

Photo of eggs cooking in a pan with the text, "Once the whites of the scallions were sautéed, I added my eggs to the pan and cooked them over medium-low heat. I stirred the eggs constantly and cooked them for around five minutes until they looked almost set, then allowed the residual heat in the pan to finish cooking them."

Photo of soft tacos with scallions, eggs, and avocado with the text, "After the eggs were finished cooking, all I had to do was assemble my tacos. Per Garten's instructions, I spooned an eighth of the scrambled eggs down the middle of each taco. Then I added the slices of avocado and the reserved scallion greens."

Photo of the completed soft tacos with the text, "I topped everything off with some salt, pepper, and Chipotle sauce. I loved how fresh Garten's dish looked. And when I checked the clock, I realized it had only taken me about 15 minutes to make breakfast tacos for four people — a huge bonus!"

node.text:
I recently spent a week at Walt Disney World in Orlando, Florida. While there, I ate most of the theme park’s fan-favorite food, like Dole Whip. Here are the snacks I liked, ones I wouldn’t order again, and how I’d rank them from worst to best.

Click the link in our bio to read more.

(Credit: Amanda Krause/Insider, Amanda Krause)
#DisneyWorld #Florida #DisneyFood

node.accessibility_caption: Photo showing Mickey Mouse ice cream bar with headline, "I tried 9 Disney World snacks that fans love, and there are 4 I'll never buy again"

Photo showing waffles with text, "My least favorite meal at Disney World were the Mickey Mouse-shaped waffles. I found that my $10 meal included three waffles, two pieces of sausage, and two strips of bacon — all of which were cold."

Photo showing the cookie with text, "I wasn't impressed with Jack Jack's Num Num cookie either. The cookie was warm and the chocolate chunks were delicious, but I didn't think the actual cookie tasted all that great. It tasted too processed for my liking."

Photo showing the Turkey leg with text, "I can understand why some people like the theme park's giant turkey legs, but I wasn't a fan.  I grew tired of it pretty quickly, and didn't understand why anyone would want to consume so much turkey at a theme park in 93-degree heat."

Photo showing the churros with text, "I also didn't love Disney World's churros. They don't live up to the hype, in my opinion. On its own, I thought the churro had a great cinnamon flavor. That being said, I also found it to be dry and underwhelming."

Photo showing the rice krispie treat with text, "Disney's Mickey-shaped, crisped-rice treats are just fine, in my opinion. The chocolate-coated side tasted pretty good, and the sprinkles added a nice crunch. The plain side, however, was a bit bland."

Photo showing the pretzel with text, "I really like Disney World's Mickey-shaped pretzels, but they can be hit or miss. The pretzel was a bit burned and crunchy on the outside, perfectly soft inside, and covered in just the right amount of salt."

Photo showing the popcorn with text, "It's almost impossible to not enjoy Disney World's buttery popcorn. Not only can you find popcorn across all four theme parks, but you can also smell it just about everywhere you go."

Photo showing the ice cream bar with text, "Mickey Mouse Premium Ice Cream Bars are classics for a reason. I personally love the mix of soft vanilla ice cream and a crunchy chocolate shell. They're simple, delicious, and perfect for hot days."

Photo showing the writer holding the Dole Whip with text, "Dole Whip is absolutely delicious — and I can't believe it took me 25 years to figure that out. It was refreshing, perfectly blended, and I couldn't believe the generous scoop you get for only a few bucks."
Photo by Food Insider on August 31, 2021. May be an image of food and text that says 'INSIDER Scientists based in Japan have successfully 3D printed a hunk of wagyu beef complete with marbling'.

node.text:
Scientists at Japan's Osaka University have proven that you don't need to kill a cow to get a prized cut of beef.

Through a technology called bioprinting, they've 3D-printed a cut of wagyu specialty steak.

The steak is composed of cell fibers taken from a cow, and assembled to create the layers of fat marbling seen in wagyu cuts.

To read more and see a video of the printing in action, click the link in our bio.

Story by Cheryl Teh.

[Credit: Kankitti Chupayoong/Shutterstock]

Click the link in our bio to watch the video.
